insights.linesPerUserTrend: GitHub Copilot shows extreme volatility with lines per user ranging from 152 to 926 weekly, including a dramatic 71% drop during the holiday weeks (Dec 23-30), while Claude Code demonstrates consistent month-over-month growth from 25K to 29K lines per user despite expanding from 6 to 24 users. Claude's specialized Agentic AI team maintains exceptionally high productivity at 89K lines per user in January, suggesting AI-assisted development tools are most effective when concentrated among dedicated power users rather than broadly distributed across traditional engineering teams.
insights.productivityComparison: Claude Code demonstrates exceptional productivity with 48,349 lines per user compared to GitHub Copilot's 2,885 lines per userâ€”a 16.8x multiplier that translates to 322.8 agentic FTEs versus just 17.1 for Copilot despite having fewer active users (28 vs 53). This stark efficiency difference suggests Claude Code users are either working on more complex, high-impact projects or the tool enables significantly deeper code generation capabilities, making it the clear productivity leader despite lower adoption rates.
insights.modelPreference: Claude dominates GitHub Copilot usage with 78% of generated code lines (118,977 lines), vastly outperforming GPT at just 9% despite GPT's market recognition. This 8.7x preference gap suggests Claude delivers superior code generation quality and developer experience, indicating organizations should prioritize Claude integration for maximum productivity gains in AI-assisted development workflows.
insights.adoptionTrend: M365 Copilot shows strong adoption momentum with users growing 26% from September to October (152 to 202 users) while maintaining consistent engagement at 44-46 prompts per user monthly. Claude Enterprise demonstrates explosive growth trajectory, scaling from 17 users in July to 101 users by January with engagement rates climbing from 28% to 42%, indicating both platforms are successfully driving productivity gains across the organization. The combined agentic FTE impact has surged from 4.8 FTEs in July to 395 FTEs by January, representing a massive 8,100% increase in organizational capacity augmentation primarily driven by Claude Code adoption generating 322.8 equivalent FTEs.
insights.engagementTrend: Claude Enterprise demonstrates explosive growth with conversations per user surging 170% from 27 to 73 between July-December, while M365 Copilot shows steady but modest adoption plateauing around 44-46 prompts per user. This engagement pattern directly correlates with productivity gains, as Claude Enterprise's higher user engagement drives 28.3 FTE productivity gains compared to M365 Copilot's 26.9 FTEs, suggesting conversation-based interactions may be more effective than prompt-based workflows for sustained business value.
insights.m365AppTrend: Teams Copilot leads adoption with 223 users in January (21% growth from September), while PowerPoint significantly lags with only 93 users despite showing the highest growth rate at 31%. The consistent upward trajectory across all apps indicates healthy enterprise adoption, but the 140-user gap between top performer (Teams) and bottom performer (PowerPoint) suggests prioritizing PowerPoint training and use case development to maximize license value.
insights.codingToolsBusinessQuestion: Given that Claude Code delivers 16.8x higher productivity per user (48,349 vs 2,885 lines) and 78% developer preference despite costing 10.5x more per seat ($200 vs $19), should we consolidate our $79,284 annual coding tool budget by migrating all 53 GitHub Copilot users to Claude Code before the March 2026 contract renewal, or implement a hybrid strategy that reserves Claude's $67,200 annual cost for the 15-20 highest-impact developers while maintaining Copilot for broader team adoption? The decision must account for whether Claude's 322.8 agentic FTE equivalent justifies potentially reducing overall tool access from 53 to 28 users within our current budget constraints.
insights.claudeEnterpriseFeatures: Only 20% of active users (24 out of 118) have created projects, while artifacts show much stronger adoption at 1,190 total creations, suggesting users readily embrace structured content generation but struggle with project organization workflows. The 5:1 artifact-to-project ratio indicates users are leveraging advanced content creation capabilities effectively but may need better onboarding for collaborative project management features. This pattern reveals a significant opportunity to convert high-engagement users (68 conversations per user) into power users through improved project workflow guidance.
insights.strategicPositioning: Given the dramatic engagement disparityâ€”Claude Enterprise users averaging 68 conversations per user versus M365 Copilot's 44 prompts per userâ€”and Claude's superior productivity multiplier generating 28.3 FTEs compared to M365's 26.9 FTEs despite having fewer total users, should these tools be positioned as complementary tiers (Claude for high-complexity creative work, M365 for routine productivity tasks) or does the data suggest consolidating investment toward Claude Enterprise given its 42% engagement rate versus M365's relatively static adoption plateau?
insights.overviewKpiMetrics:
High user engagement is evident with 68 conversations per user and 48,349 lines of code generated per user, indicating Claude Enterprise is being actively utilized for substantial development work rather than casual interactions. The 17,021 files uploaded against 1,190 artifacts generated suggests users are primarily leveraging Claude for code analysis and consultation rather than net-new content creation, pointing to a mature adoption pattern focused on enhancing existing work.

The substantial code generation volume of 1.35 million lines across 118 users demonstrates significant productivity impact, with each user generating enough code equivalent to multiple software projects. This high-volume usage pattern, combined with the relatively low artifact-to-conversation ratio (1 artifact per 7 conversations), indicates Claude is being used more for iterative development assistance and problem-solving than for creating standalone deliverables.
insights.monthlyGrowthChart:
Active Users demonstrate consistent month-over-month growth from 17 in July to 101 in January, representing a 494% increase over six months with accelerating adoption rates in recent months. The user base expanded by 19% in December and 18.8% in January, indicating sustained momentum in platform adoption.

Conversations peaked at 6,223 in December before dropping 62% to 2,361 in January, while Lines of Code usage exploded from zero to 698,089 lines in just three months since its November launch. This suggests a significant shift in user behavior patterns, with coding activities gaining substantial traction even as conversational usage experiences seasonal fluctuation.
insights.adoptionOutputTrends: User adoption demonstrates steady linear growth from 17 to 101 active users (494% increase), while output generation reveals a dramatic inflection point in November when code generation capabilities were introduced, triggering explosive productivity gains from near-zero to 698K lines of code by January. The platform achieved remarkable efficiency scaling where a 31% user increase from November to January (77 to 101 users) coincided with a 364% surge in code output, indicating that established users rapidly amplified their productivity once advanced code generation features became available.
insights.departmentInsights:
TechCo Inc demonstrates exceptionally strong AI adoption with 47% of employees actively using Claude Enterprise, significantly outpacing typical software vendor benchmarks of 20-30% for conversational AI tools. The 68 conversations per user indicates deep, sustained engagement rather than superficial trial usage, suggesting employees have successfully integrated AI into their daily workflows.

Engineering shows concentrated but highly productive Claude Code usage with 28 active users generating an impressive 48,349 lines per user, indicating the development team has achieved meaningful productivity gains through AI-assisted coding. This usage intensity far exceeds industry averages and demonstrates successful technical adoption among the core product development function.

The stark contrast between broad Enterprise adoption (118 users) and narrow Code adoption (28 users) reveals a significant opportunity gap, as most B2B SaaS companies typically see 40-60% of their technical workforce adopting coding assistants. TechCo Inc's current 11% technical adoption rate suggests substantial untapped potential for expanding Claude Code usage across product, QA, and technical operations teams.

Strategic focus should prioritize expanding Claude Code adoption within the existing technical organization through targeted training and use case demonstrations, while simultaneously identifying high-value Enterprise use cases in customer success and sales operations where the proven engagement patterns can drive revenue impact.
insights.m365PowerUsers: Customer Success dominates power user adoption with 11 of the top 20 users (55%), generating an average of 1,465 prompts per user compared to the organization average of 5.6 prompts per day. The highest performers demonstrate two distinct usage patterns: intensive burst users like Ellie Berger (63.3 prompts/day over 34 days) and consistent daily users like Ambra Hubenthal (30.3 prompts/day over 112 days), both achieving agenticFTE scores above 0.6. Organizations should prioritize Customer Success teams for advanced Copilot training and use their cross-application usage patterns (86-100% app usage scores) as templates for scaling adoption across other departments.
insights.m365AppAdoption: Teams Copilot leads adoption at 89.4% (219 users), while PowerPoint Copilot significantly lags at just 36.3% (89 users) - creating a 53-point gap compared to Word's 64.5% adoption rate. This represents a critical opportunity to unlock 69 additional PowerPoint users who are already active with Word Copilot, potentially generating 35 additional AI-assisted presentations monthly. The strong performance of communication tools (Teams 89.4%, Outlook 73.5%) versus content creation apps suggests users prioritize collaborative AI features over document authoring assistance.
insights.m365DepartmentPerformance: Partnerships (649.5 prompts/user, 12.03 prompts/day) and Marketing (434.4 prompts/user, 10.7 prompts/day) lead adoption with exceptional engagement, while Engineering represents the largest untapped opportunity with 70 users averaging only 157.1 prompts and 27.7 active days. The stark contrast between high-performing customer-facing departments and lagging technical teams suggests targeted enablement for Engineering and Product could unlock significant productivity gains across 87 additional users.
insights.m365Opportunities: Engineering department represents the largest opportunity with 12 of 17 low-engagement users (71%) showing minimal adoption despite having technical expertise that should drive higher usage. PowerPoint Copilot has the lowest adoption at 36.3% compared to 89.4% for Teams, creating a 69-user gap worth 35 additional presentations monthly. Immediate actions: reclaim 9 inactive licenses for $171 monthly savings, launch targeted PowerPoint training for the 69 non-adopters, and implement department-specific enablement for Engineering to unlock their underutilized $204 monthly investment.
insights.m365MonthlyGrowthTrends: M365 Copilot shows concerning artifact generation decline of 45% from October's peak of 533 to January's 294, despite maintaining stable user base around 192-199 active users and consistent prompt volume of 8,300-9,200. This pattern suggests users are increasingly relying on Copilot Chat rather than creating tangible Word/Excel/PowerPoint deliverables, indicating potential underutilization of M365 Copilot's core productivity value proposition for document creation and collaborative work output.
insights.m365AgentsAdoption: User-created agents dominate M365 Copilot adoption with 57% of all agent combinations (86 out of 151), led by the "BDR Cold Outreach Builder" which generated 318 responses across 10 users, followed by "MEDDPICC Coach" with 68 responses and "CI Spy" with 59 responses. Marketing departments drive the highest agent engagement with 298 total responses, while Sales-Enterprise and Customer Success each contribute significant usage with 71 and 160 responses respectively. The success of specialized user-created agents like the sales-focused MEDDPICC Coach and competitive intelligence CI Spy reveals strong demand for department-specific automation tools, suggesting organizations should prioritize scaling these grassroots innovations into enterprise-wide solutions to maximize the 44 prompts per user engagement rate across their 192 active M365 users.
insights.m365VirtualFteImpact: M365 Copilot reached peak effectiveness in October with 28.3 FTE equivalents and 202 users, but has since plateaued at 26.9 FTEs with declining user adoption from 202 to 192 users over the past three months. While the tool maintains consistent productivity output of approximately 4,650 hours saved monthly, the stagnant growth suggests potential adoption barriers or user experience challenges that need addressing to unlock further organizational capacity gains.
insights.claudeEnterpriseDepartmentPerformance: Marketing leads enterprise adoption with power user Kia Brenes driving 1,025 conversations and generating 4.39 agentic FTE, while Product demonstrates the highest value density through Sara Johnson's artifact-heavy usage (298 artifacts) delivering 9.41 agentic FTE from just 17 users. The stark contrast between departments reveals that Marketing excels at conversational volume and broad adoption, whereas Product and specialized teams like Agentic AI (Luis Amadeo with 170 artifacts) are leveraging Claude's generative capabilities to create tangible business outputs at significantly higher productivity multipliers.
insights.claudeEnterpriseVirtualFteImpact: Claude Enterprise demonstrates exceptional growth momentum with 495% FTE impact increase from July to January (4.8 to 28.3 FTEs) and 494% user adoption growth (17 to 101 users), significantly outpacing other AI tools in organizational scaling. While Claude Code delivers the highest absolute productivity impact at 322.8 FTEs in January, Claude Enterprise shows the strongest month-over-month acceleration with 18.9% FTE growth from December to January, indicating superior user engagement and expanding use cases across the organization.
insights.claudeCodeDepartmentPerformance: The Agentic AI team demonstrates exceptional Claude Code adoption with 176,740 lines per user compared to Engineering's 13,705 lines per user - a 12.9x productivity multiplier that translates to 247 equivalent FTEs versus Engineering's 71. Top performer lamadeo from Agentic AI generated 287,764 lines of code, nearly 4x more than Engineering's leading contributor dselikhov at 73,924 lines. This dramatic productivity gap suggests AI-native teams are leveraging Claude Code far more effectively than traditional engineering departments, indicating significant untapped potential for broader organizational adoption.
insights.crossPlatformDepartmentComparison: Customer Success demonstrates remarkable M365 Copilot adoption with 395 prompts per user compared to just 116 Claude conversations per user, while Engineering shows the inverse pattern with 13,705 lines of code generated per user in Claude Code versus only 157 M365 prompts per user. The Agentic AI team exhibits extreme Claude specialization, generating 176,740 lines of code per user while averaging merely 57 M365 prompts, revealing how technical teams gravitate toward Claude's coding capabilities while customer-facing departments maximize M365's integrated workflow benefits. This bifurcation suggests that conversational AI tools like M365 Copilot excel in communication-heavy roles, while Claude's technical depth serves development-intensive functions, with Marketing uniquely leveraging both platforms effectively (434 M365 prompts and 2,723 Claude messages per user).
insights.departmentAdoptionHeatmap:
**Top Performers:** Agentic AI leads with an exceptional 97 score, achieving 3 seats per employee and 90K+ activity per employee, demonstrating the power of deep multi-tool integration. Product (84) and Marketing (83) follow with strong multi-tool usage (1.88 and 1.58 seats/employee respectively) and consistent engagement, establishing these creative departments as AI adoption champions.

**Growth Opportunities:** Engineering (76) shows solid foundation with 94 users but limited multi-tool exploration (1.13 seats/employee), representing the biggest opportunity for expanding creative AI workflows given their technical aptitude. Sales - Large Market (79) and Operations (78) have good multi-tool usage but need activity intensity improvements to reach excellence tier.

**Enablement Priorities:** Customer Success presents the most critical gap - despite having 80 employees (largest department), they score only 54 with minimal multi-tool usage (1.0 seats/employee) and low engagement (227 activity/employee). Finance (45), Sales - Enterprise (53), and Legal (40) need comprehensive enablement programs addressing both coverage and engagement fundamentals.

**Multi-Tool Champions:** Agentic AI's 3.0 seats per employee ratio delivers 43x higher activity per employee than single-tool departments, proving that creative multi-tool workflows drive exponential productivity gains. Product and Operations also demonstrate strong multi-tool adoption (1.88 and 1.83 respectively) with proportionally higher business impact.

**Strategic Recommendations:** Launch targeted multi-tool training programs for Engineering to unlock their 94-user potential, implement Customer Success-specific AI use case workshops to address the largest adoption gap, and create cross-department showcases where Agentic AI and Product teams demonstrate their successful multi-tool workflows to accelerate organization-wide creative adoption.
insights.expansionOpportunitiesExplanation:
Our dual scoring system combines behavioral analytics (115-point scale measuring actual AI usage patterns) with department-specific baselines (10-35% based on role complexity) to determine Premium seat allocation. The system uses MAX logic, selecting whichever method yields a higher Premium countâ€”ensuring departments get adequate coverage whether driven by demonstrated high usage or inherent job complexity requirements.

M365 Copilot engagement data from 156 users without Claude Enterprise provides crucial expansion signals, identifying high-potential candidates through metrics like daily prompt intensity and consistency patterns. This cross-platform intelligence reveals users already demonstrating AI readiness who would benefit from Claude's advanced capabilities, particularly in departments like Customer Success where only 6 users currently qualify behaviorally but 20 are needed based on role requirements.

Department baselines reflect varying analytical complexity, with Engineering requiring 100% Premium coverage due to code generation needs, while Finance and Product get 35% baselines for complex analytical work, and Sales receives 20% for client-facing analysis. This tiered approach ensures Premium features reach users whose roles inherently demand advanced AI capabilities, regardless of current usage patterns.

Value calculations multiply projected time savings by department-specific hourly rates minus licensing costs, with Engineering showing exceptional 31.4x ROI due to proven productivity multipliers from code generation. The $406,854 monthly net benefit across all departments demonstrates how behavioral scoring identifies genuine productivity opportunities while baseline coverage ensures strategic capability deployment.
insights.rolloutStrategyExplanation:
**Priority Sequencing Rationale**
Our value-optimized rollout prioritizes departments by monthly net benefit rather than ROI percentage alone, ensuring we capture the most dollar value quickly while maintaining positive returns. Engineering leads with $317,016 monthly net benefit at 31.4x ROI, followed by Customer Success at $49,255 net benefit, creating a front-loaded value capture strategy that reduces financial risk if later phases encounter delays.

**Phased Rollout Approach**
Phase 1 targets quick wins like Engineering, Product, and Marketingâ€”departments with existing user bases (34, 16, and 17 current users respectively) and high power user concentrations that minimize change management risk. Phase 2 scales to Customer Success and Sales teams where medium ROI (9.5x-9.9x) combines with proven use cases from Phase 1, while Phase 3 addresses smaller departments like Finance, HR, and IT that require more enablement but still deliver 4.2x-7.1x ROI.

**Success Metrics and Tracking**
We'll track adoption rates above 80% in Phase 1 departments, premium qualification rates above 50% for behavior-driven recommendations, and usage intensity increases above 30% in Phase 2 scaling departments. The overall 1-month payback period across all phases validates our sequencing strategy, with cumulative value tracking showing how the $406,854 total monthly net benefit compounds as each phase deploys successfully.
insights.virtualFteImpact:
The organization has achieved explosive AI productivity growth, reaching 395 Agentic FTEs in January 2026â€”equivalent to adding nearly 400 full-time employees without hiring. This represents a remarkable 26.4% month-over-month increase and an 8,125% surge since July 2025, driven primarily by Claude Code's dominance at 322.8 FTEs (82% of total impact) as coding AI adoption accelerated from zero to 24 active users.

The productivity transformation accelerated dramatically in November 2025 when coding tools launched, catapulting total capacity from 44 FTEs to 151 FTEs in a single month. Claude Code now delivers 38x more productivity impact than traditional productivity tools like M365 Copilot, highlighting how specialized AI coding assistance creates exponentially higher value per user than general productivity enhancement.

Current trajectory indicates the organization is capturing over 68,000 productive hours monthly through AIâ€”equivalent to expanding workforce capacity by 20% without traditional hiring costs. The sustained 26% monthly growth rate suggests AI adoption is entering an acceleration phase where coding productivity gains are becoming the primary driver of organizational capacity expansion.
insights.integrationsOverview: Product teams dominate Claude Enterprise MCP usage with 7,163 calls (30% of total) and the highest per-user intensity at 478 calls, while Atlassian integration leads with 8,044 calls across 56 users, indicating strong project management workflow adoption. Power users like Sara Johnson (2,257 calls) and specialized tools like Sweep (409 calls per user in Revenue Operations) reveal significant productivity gains in specific use cases, but 20 underutilized integrations suggest major expansion opportunities across departments with lower engagement like HR and Finance.
insights.projectsOverview: Luis from Agentic AI dominates project creation with 22 high-sophistication projects (62 avg score) and 73 documents, representing 10% of all projects despite being just one of 54 creators. The 82% inactive project rate and low document adoption (50 of 231 projects) indicates most users create basic projects without leveraging knowledge management features, missing opportunities for sustained productivity gains. Marketing and Sales departments show strong prompt template adoption (37/48 and 23/27 projects respectively) but need document integration to match Agentic AI's comprehensive approach.
insights.ecosystemComparison: M365 Copilot shows concerning shallow adoption with only 32% of agents actively used (48/151) and extreme concentration where the top BDR agent captures 318 responses from just 10 users, while Claude Enterprise demonstrates deeper organizational maturity with 231 sophisticated projects averaging 38 complexity points and 23,511 integration calls across 30 MCP connectors. Claude's ecosystem reveals true AI transformation with power users like Sara Johnson executing 2,257 integration calls across 11 different systems, compared to M365's pattern of repetitive, single-purpose agent usage primarily in Marketing departments. With the March 2026 Microsoft contract renewal approaching, organizations should evaluate whether M365's agent-response volume model delivers less strategic value than Claude's project sophistication and integration depth that enables complex, cross-functional AI workflows.

PRESENTER NOTES:
We're witnessing an incredible transformation in how we work. Our Claude Enterprise deployment, which includes both Standard seats for conversations and Premium seats with Claude Code for development, is generating massive productivity gains. PRESENTER NOTES:
Our power users are showing us what's possible when we fully embrace AI capabilities. The productivity multipliers are staggering - Claude Code users are generating nearly 17 times more output than traditional coding tools. We're seeing clear patterns where departments that adopt multiple AI tools and create structured workflows achieve exponentially higher results. The key is moving beyond basic usage to creating projects, leveraging integrations, and building repeatable processes that compound over time.

TITLE: Expanding Our AI-Powered Future

â€¢ Customer Success (54/100 adoption score) and Finance (45/100) represent biggest expansion opportunities with 80+ employees ready for enablement

â€¢ Share feedback in #claude-enterprise, #claude-code-dev, #ai-collab, and #techco-thrv - your input directly influences our AI roadmap

We're taking a data-driven approach to expansion that prioritizes departments where AI will have the biggest impact. Customer Success and Finance represent our largest untapped opportunities, with hundreds of employees who could benefit from the productivity gains we're seeing elsewhere. The upcoming Microsoft contract renewal gives us a strategic decision point to optimize our tool mix based on real usage patterns. We're not expanding for the sake of it - every rollout decision is backed by ROI analysis and department readiness scores. Your feedback in our Slack channels directly shapes these decisions, so please keep sharing your experiences and ideas.
